Last week, Roy Walker '69, a black
student, filed charges in Justice of the
Peace Court in Grinnell against a man
who he identified as having passed him
in a car and shorter racial sluts at him.
Vernon Schooley of Grinnell pleased
guilty to the charge of disturbance of the
peace and was fixed $25.
Schooley was in a car with three or
four others when they passed Walker
last Thursday and shorter racial sluts,
such as “bigger", at him. when the car
passed, Walker tried to get the license
number, but the car was too dirty for
him to read it. Knowing from past experience that they would probably be
back, he wanted, and when they are
placed again, he copied the license number from the front of the car. He then
gave this information to the Grinnell
Police Department, and Schooley was
picked up within a half hour.
Although others in the car, continue
tion workers in their early agencies,
had also shorter these sluts at him,
Walker could only relatively identify
Schooley, so he only tried one complaint.
This was the first time, however, that a
complaint had been tried, although this
harassment “is not unusual at all,” according to Walker.
Walker said that incidents like this one
occur “constantly," and there have been
cases involving visiting black directories,
as well as black students Usually, however, the students are unable to get the
license number of the car.
Grinnell Police Chief Bill meters told
the 58:}! that this is the first time any
such case has gone into court, since the
calendars have been juveniles in all the
previous cases he knew oil in these
