By JONATHAN STEIN
The book store committee is almost
ready to give their final recommends-
(sons concerning next year's Bookstore.
The committee, completed oi Mr. Moore,
Mr. personnel, Mr. Muchmote, Mark
pass, Henry Scheft, and Jonathan klein
will make the following proposals.
The College should concerns of the
Bookstore as a service to the college
community. There is no place within 50
miles of Grinneil where quality books
and peripherals can be purchased and
access to quality books and peripherals
is essential to a liberal arts education,
It is obvious that the college can never
have an adequate Bookstore in the space
now allocated. The women's Gym, when
available and properly generated, will be
ideal. Until the Gym in available. the
Bookstore should be located in one oi
the vacant ﬂoops in the office building:
on 5th street.
We are aware that this temporary location will be somewhat inconvenient,
but the need of a good Bookstore is so
urgent that the temporary inconvenience
is more than asset by the availability oi
adequate space. .
The committee also will recommend
that texts required for college courses
be distributed from behind the counter
at a special center on campus. Prearranged candles of books for Each course
should be made up in advance to speed
up the distribution. It would also he possible to buy any book single at the center
but considering that the majority oi students buy their books at one time this
plan would speed up the entire operas
civil.
This plan would be more convenient
for students, since there would be less
crossing, searching for books, standing
in line with heavy loads, etc. and should
cut down considerable on thettr This
special distribution center would be open
for the first two or three weeks of each
semester; alter this time a few copies
of each text would be kept in the Bookstore for late purchases.
The committee will also recommend
that there should be a standing committee, probably three faculty and threstudents, to work with the Bookstore
manager on stopping books and materials.
The committee strongly recommends
that any student should be able to order
any book at any time through the bookstore. Such is not the case at the present
time.
Quality magazines and peripherals definitely belong in the bookstore.
Students should be hired when opening:
are available in bookstore personnel.
Used books, new and used records.
posters, prints, and art materials will
hopefully be included in the new book»store.
The Committee emphasizes the need
for a quality bookstore that will be an
integral part or the intellectual environment of Grinnell College.
The need for a better bookstore has
existed too long. It is hoped that the administration will give the matter top priority so that R quality bookstore will be
a reality in September.
 
